honestly how limited my money supply is, and how much I have to run away from the consequences of overspending. I think it also has to do with my parents — despite their good intentions, they’re really strict and need to butt in a lot, so my notions of spending or saving my money are affected by their advice and judgements, which isn’t always what I want.

I think that generally speaking, I yearn for more freedom to not have advisors and parents and money supervisors (but honestly for now I need to wise up a little more, because my parents are usually right and I learn it the hard way).

I think what I will benefit the most from listening to this was…JUST LISTS!

I have to disagree a little bit on this. Although a written record of your finances is good, it is not necessarily the ticket to liberty. Even if you know how much you have, if you are someone in debt, your constraints are even worse. (Sadly, this is a real problem for most Singaporeans today.)
